statement:
Let A be a $2\times{2}$ matrix which transforms

\begin{align*}\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
1
\end{bmatrix} \quad \text{to} \quad \begin{bmatrix}
2\\
2
\end{bmatrix}\end{align*}

and transforms

\begin{align*}\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
-1
\end{bmatrix} \quad \text{to} \quad \begin{bmatrix}
0\\
0
\end{bmatrix}.\end{align*}

What is the matrix A?

sols:
Let's write our matrix A as

\begin{align*}A=
\begin{bmatrix}
a  &  b\\
c  &  d
\end{bmatrix}\end{align*}

with yet to be determined entries. In the problem we know that

\begin{align*}A
\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
-1
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
a  &  b\\
c  &  d
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
-1
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
0\\
0
\end{bmatrix}\end{align*}

and we expand this out to get

\begin{align*}
a-b&=0,\\
c-d&=0.\end{align*}

Therefore, \emph{a=b} and \emph{c=d}. We also have that

\begin{align*}A
\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
1
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
a  &  b\\
c  &  d
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
1
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
2\\
2
\end{bmatrix}\end{align*}

which we can expand out to get

\begin{align*}
a+b=2a&=2,\\
c+d=2c&=2.\end{align*}

Therefore we conclude that \emph{a=b=c=d=1}. Therefore our matrix
\emph{A} is

\begin{align*}A=
\begin{bmatrix}
1  &  1\\
1  &  1
\end{bmatrix}.\end{align*}

Notice that we can indeed confirm that this matrix has eigenvalues 2 and
0 and is not invertible.
